1. SPRING MVC OVERVIEW
=======================

1.1 Definition:
Spring MVC (Model‚ÄìView‚ÄìController) is a web framework of the Spring ecosystem that follows the MVC design pattern to build loosely coupled, scalable, and testable web applications.

1.2 Why Spring MVC:
Clean separation of concerns
Easy integration with Spring Core, AOP, Security
Supports RESTful services
Flexible view technologies
Production-ready framework

1.3 MVC Pattern:
Model:
Definition:
Represents application data and business logic.
Examples:
POJO
DTO
Entity

View:
Definition:
Responsible for rendering UI.

Examples:
JSP
Thymeleaf
HTML / JSON

Controller:
Definition:
Handles HTTP requests, interacts with model, and returns view/response.

2. SPRING MVC ARCHITECTURE
============================

2.1 DispatcherServlet:
Definition:
Central Front Controller that handles all incoming requests.

Key Points:
First entry point
Configured automatically in Spring Boot
Delegates to controller

2.2 Spring MVC Request Flow:
Client sends request
DispatcherServlet receives request
HandlerMapping finds controller
Controller processes request
Returns Model/View or Response
ViewResolver resolves view
Response sent to client

3. CONTROLLER LAYER
====================

3.1 @Controller:
Definition:
Marks class as MVC controller that returns views.

Example:
@Controller
public class HomeController {

    @GetMapping("/home")
    public String home() {
        return "home";
    }
}

Explanation:
Returns logical view name
ViewResolver maps to JSP/HTML

3.2 @RestController:
Definition:
Combination of:
@Controller + @ResponseBody

Example:
@RestController
public class HelloController {

    @GetMapping("/hello")
    public String hello() {
        return "Hello Spring MVC";
    }
}

Output:
Hello Spring MVC
Key Points:
Used for REST APIs
Returns JSON/String directly

3.3 Difference: @Controller vs @RestController:
@Controller	@RestController
Returns view	Returns data
Used for MVC	Used for REST
Needs @ResponseBody	Auto included

4. REQUEST MAPPING
===================
4.1 @RequestMapping:
Definition:

Maps HTTP requests to handler methods.

Example:
@RequestMapping(value = "/test", method = RequestMethod.GET)
public String test() {
    return "test";
}

4.2 Shortcut Mapping Annotations:
@GetMapping
@PostMapping
@PutMapping
@DeleteMapping
@PatchMapping

4.3 Example:
@GetMapping("/user")
public String getUser() {
    return "User fetched";
}

Output:
User fetched

5. HANDLING REQUEST DATA
==========================

5.1 @RequestParam:
Definition:
Extracts query parameters from URL.

Example:
@GetMapping("/user")
public String user(@RequestParam String name) {
    return "User: " + name;
}

URL:
/user?name=Sai

Output:
User: Sai

5.2 @PathVariable:
Definition:
Extracts path variable from URL.

Example:
@GetMapping("/user/{id}")
public String user(@PathVariable int id) {
    return "ID: " + id;
}

URL:
/user/101

Output:
ID: 101

5.3 @RequestBody:
Definition:

Maps HTTP request body to Java object.

Example:
@PostMapping("/save")
public User save(@RequestBody User user) {
    return user;
}

Output:
JSON response of User

5.4 @ResponseBody:
Definition:

Writes return value directly to HTTP response body.

üìå Included by default in @RestController.

6. MODEL HANDLING
==================

6.1 Model:
@GetMapping("/data")
public String data(Model model) {
    model.addAttribute("msg", "Hello MVC");
    return "view";
}

6.2 ModelAndView:
@GetMapping("/mv")
public ModelAndView test() {
    ModelAndView mv = new ModelAndView("view");
    mv.addObject("msg", "Hello");
    return mv;
}

7. VIEW RESOLUTION
===================

7.1 ViewResolver:
Definition:

Resolves logical view name to actual view.

Example:
spring.mvc.view.prefix=/WEB-INF/views/
spring.mvc.view.suffix=.jsp

8. EXCEPTION HANDLING
======================

8.1 @ExceptionHandler:
@ExceptionHandler(Exception.class)
public String handle() {
    return "error";
}

8.2 @ControllerAdvice / @RestControllerAdvice:
Definition:

Provides global exception handling.

@RestControllerAdvice
public class GlobalExceptionHandler {
}

9. VALIDATION
==============

9.1 @Valid:
@PostMapping("/save")
public void save(@Valid @RequestBody User user) {}

9.2 Validation Annotations:
@NotNull
@Size
@Email

10. RESPONSE HANDLING
======================

10.1 ResponseEntity:
return ResponseEntity.ok(data);

10.2 @ResponseStatus:
@ResponseStatus(HttpStatus.NOT_FOUND)

11. SPRING MVC vs SPRING BOOT MVC
==================================

Spring MVC	Spring Boot MVC
Manual config	Auto config
External server	Embedded server
More setup	Faster

12. THREAD SAFETY
==================

12.1 Controller Scope:

Controllers are singleton
Must be stateless
Avoid shared mutable variables

13. REAL-TIME BEST PRACTICES
=============================

‚úî Use @RestController for APIs
‚úî Keep controllers thin
‚úî Use DTOs
‚úî Centralize exception handling
‚úî Validate input
‚úî Avoid business logic in controller

14. MOST ASKED INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
===================================

14.1 What is DispatcherServlet?
Front controller of Spring MVC.

14.2 Is Spring MVC thread-safe?
Framework is safe; developer code decides safety.

14.3 Difference between @RequestParam and @PathVariable?
Query param vs URL path.

14. Can one controller handle multiple URLs?
‚úÖ Yes

